comments: Finney-Smith (DAL) maintains a legal guarding position alongside James (LAL), and incidental contact occurs as they come together during the drive.
Westbrook (LAL) has his foot on the line and is in the paint for longer than three seconds without imminently actively guarding an opponent.
Reaves (LAL) maintains a legal guarding position and absorbs the contact created by Hardaway Jr. (DAL) during the driving shot attempt.
Brunson (DAL) is in the paint for less than three seconds when he is imminently exiting.
Westbrook (LAL) makes clean ball contact to temporarily dislodge the rebound from Porzingis (DAL).
Brunson (DAL) maintains a legal guarding position on James (LAL) during the drive.
Ellington's (LAL) shot does not touch the basket and goes out of bounds. The Mavericks are correctly awarded possession.
Westbrook (LAL) reaches across Brunson's (DAL) body and makes contact with his arm after he gathers the ball, which affects his driving shot attempt.
James (LAL) gathers on his left foot and establishes his left as his pivot after lifting his right foot while stationary. He then lifts and re-plants his pivot foot before releasing his shot.
Davis (LAL) makes clean ball contact to dislodge the rebound from Kleber (DAL).
During the screen, Reaves (LAL) and Hardaway Jr. (DAL) mutually engage and disengage and the contact is marginal.
Westbrook (LAL) legally contests Burke's (DAL) jump shot attempt.  Any "high-five" contact after the release is considered incidental.
Finney-Smith (DAL) maintains a legal guarding position on James (LAL) at the end of the drive.
Ellington (LAL) makes clean ball contact to deflect the pass away from Porzingis (DAL) and the ball goes out of bounds. Possession is correctly awarded to the Mavericks.
During the inbounds, Hardaway Jr. (DAL) briefly places his hand on James' (LAL) side, and marginal contact occurs as he immediately removes it.
Kleber (DAL) establishes himself in Westbrook's (LAL) path and absorbs the contact at the end of the drive.
Finney-Smith (DAL) reaches for the ball and marginal contact occurs as he brushes Westbrook's (LAL) arm, which does not affect his ability to make his intended pass.
Finney-Smith (DAL) has his hands on Davis' (LAL) side and marginal contact occurs during his play at the basket.
Hardaway Jr. (DAL) and Reaves (LAL) come together as they pursue the loose ball, causing incidental contact to occur.
Porzingis (DAL) momentarily places a resting hand on James' (LAL) back and marginal contact occurs during his dunk attempt.
Porzingis (DAL) extends his leg slightly while establishing himself in Ellington's (LAL) path, and marginal foot-to-foot contact occurs, which does not affect Ellington's ability to defend.
Brunson (DAL) maintains a legal guarding position on James (LAL) during the drive.
Kleber (DAL) briefly grasps and immediately releases Davis' (LAL) jersey as marginal contact occurs off-ball.
Porzingis (DAL) is in the paint for longer than three seconds without imminently actively guarding an opponent.
Kleber (DAL) legally contests Westbrook's (LAL) jump shot attempt.  Any "high-five" contact after the release is considered incidental.
Brunson (DAL) comes to a stop and maintains his pivot foot prior to passing the ball.
Davis (LAL) establishes himself in a somewhat wide screening position and marginal contact occurs with Brunson's (DAL) side, which does not affect his ability to defend.
Westbrook (LAL) splits his feet at the start of his dribble.
Davis (LAL) could be deemed to be in the lane for about three seconds when the shot is imminent.

Hardaway Jr. (DAL) jumps to the side of Reaves (LAL) to contest the shot, and marginal contact occurs as he brushes Reaves' side on his follow-through. Hardaway Jr. also makes incidental "high-five" contact after Reaves' release.
